  pass through module methods on a new Gem::UserInteraction module.  Those
  methods will be the method of abstracting the interaction of RubyGems for use
  in a GUI-based solution.  

2004-06-10  Richard Kilmer <rich@infoether.com>

  * rubygems/ChangeLog, rubygems/bin/gem,
  rubygems/examples/application/an-app.gemspec,
  rubygems/gemspecs/cgikit-1.1.0.gemspec, rubygems/gemspecs/jabber4r.gemspec,
  rubygems/gemspecs/linguistics.gemspec, rubygems/gemspecs/ook.gemspec,
  rubygems/gemspecs/progressbar.gemspec, rubygems/gemspecs/redcloth.gemspec,
  rubygems/gemspecs/rublog.gemspec, rubygems/gemspecs/ruby-doom.gemspec,
  rubygems/gemspecs/rubyjdwp.gemspec, rubygems/gemspecs/statistics.gemspec,
  rubygems/install.rb, rubygems/lib/rubygems.rb,
  rubygems/lib/rubygems/builder.rb, rubygems/test/bogussources.rb,
  rubygems/test/functional.rb, rubygems/test/insure_session.rb,
  rubygems/test/test_builder.rb, rubygems/test/test_cache.rb,
  rubygems/test/test_format.rb, rubygems/test/test_remote_installer.rb,
  rubygems/test/test_specification.rb, rubygems/test/test_validator.rb,
  rubygems/test/test_version_comparison.rb: * require 'rubygems' now minimally
  requires only the files needed for runtime access to gems...not management of
  gems.  To manage gems you now additionally need to execute Gem::manage_gems
  prior to using the builder/installer/etc.  This makes gemspecs not backward
  compatible unless they add that line to the gemspec after the require
  'rubygems' line.  

